@Node "intro"
@{jcenter}
@{B}@{U}Introduction@{UU}@{UB}
@{jleft}
	This guide is just something I whipped up quickly, which means I didn't spell/grammer/usage check it. Anyway, I wrote this program in part to learn how MUI works, so it might (probably will) be buggy as hell.
	Also, I wrote it because I needed a quick and easy way to lock my computer, sometimes remotely, and keep it locked after a reboot/power cycle. Aminet is littered with programs that do similar, but none of them really did it for me, but they might work better for you than this one. (I happen to be a sucker for eye candy, so this thing probably isn't the most efficent for a low-spec Amiga).
	The 2 things I really @{B}@{I}needed@{UI}@{UB} were the ability to trigger the lock-out via an arexx command, and the ability to remember if it was locked or not during a reboot (Very clever 5-yo daughter now knows whatever is running goes away after a reset, including password requesters...)
	For the arexx command to work, I needed it to hide in the commodities and wait for its command (which I can now send via text-message on my phoe to my e-mail address, where YAM will trigger the thing if needed). The second thing is easily done with some clever scripting and some of the other password proggies out there, but that seems rathr "inelegant" to me..
	Anyway, enough blabbing. What you probably want to know @{"here" LINK "usage"}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "requirements"
@{jcenter}
@{B}@{U}Requirements@{UB}@{UU}
@{jleft}

@{B}Hardware@{UB}

	@{B}An Amiga@{UB}. Or an emulator. 68000 OCS should even work (with @{"68000 betterstring" system "openurl http://aminet.net/package/dev/mui/MCC_BetterString_68k"}). Not sure why you would want this on an emulator, though..
	
	@{B}Kickstart 3.x@{UB} or greater. I think. I've tested it under 3.0 and 3.9, and it wowrked.
	
	@{B}1MB RAM@{UB} @{I}should@{UI} be fine, but I've not tested it. MUI can get kinda hungary at times, and I'm hardly a seasoned programmer when it comes to optimization. Of course, the more options used, the more memory needed.
	
@{B}Software@{UB}

	@{"MUI" system "openurl http://aminet.net/package/util/libs/mui38usr"}          	On Aminet, in util/libs/mui38usr.lha.
	
	@{"BetterString" system "openurl http://aminet.net/package/dev/mui/MCC_BetterString-11.21"} 	on Aminet, in dev/mui/MCC_BetterString-11.21.lha.
		@{B}OR@{UB}
	@{"68000 version" system "openurl http://aminet.net/package/dev/mui/MCC_BetterString_68k"}	on Aminet, dev/mui/MCC_BetterString_68k.lha.
	
	@{"MCC_GIFAnim" system "openurl http://aminet.net/package/dev/mui/MCC_GIFAnim"}  		On Aminet, dev/mui/MCC_GIFAnim.lha.
	
	I'm also going to compile a "lite" version that uses regular string gadgets, and no sounds or gif anims. Which would be @{B}MUCH@{UB} more efficient on a 68000 based 2.x system (Like an A600).
	
@ENDNODE

@NODE "install"
@{jcenter}
@{B}@{U}Installation@{UU}@{UB}
@{jleft}

	Pretty easy, though it depends on how you want to use it. If you're planning on launching from the workbench, e.g. left-out workbench icon, anywhere you copy it is fine. Just remember that the default sounds and logos look in the same directory, so if you move 'em, you have to reconfigure 'em.
	If you put it in your WBstartup drawer, make sure that either @{B}DONOTWAIT@{UB} is in the tooltypes, or that you can type quickly. Otherwise, Workbench complains with a requester.
	If you start it from a shell, remember its a MUI app, most of which require a stack size of 8192. typing @{B}stack 8192@{UB} before will fix this. Same thing with a script. If you're launching via startup-sequence or user-startup, it needs to go after the MUI assigns.
	Also, if you use @{"Wbstartup++" system "openurl http://aminet.net/package/util/boot/wbstartup++"} (or similar), You want to avoid putting this in the wbstartup/enabled directory, as WBstartup++ has an option to disable all wbstartup programs with a hotkey, making this program rather useless. I'd recommend putting it in the WBstartup drawer with a start priority set to before the wbstartup++ program. See @{"limitations" link "limitations"} for more info. (I use WBstartup++, and can't live without it myself. Thanks, Frank Fenn! :D)
	
@ENDNODE

@NODE "usage"
@{jcenter}
@{B}@{U}Usage@{UB}@{UU}
@{jleft}

	When you start the program, it doesn't have any username/password information saved. So it'll ask @{"you for it" link "screenshots/1_1st_run.iff/main"}. Just type whatever you want to @{"set it" link "screenshots/2_entering_password.iff/main"}. If you go to the settings, click save, then close without entering a username, it will still bug you for one, and eat whatever settings you entered before (a small bug that I've not felt the need to squish yet). 
	Click the save button, and it @{"logs you out" link "screenshots/3_saved.iff/main"}. It doesn't clear your username and password from the string gadgets @{B}this time@{UB}, so just click the @{"log in button" link "screenshots/4_loggedin.iff/main"}. It turns into a close button, and the lock and settings buttons activate.
	@{B}Lock@{UB} button just logs back out (disabling the settings button, and changing Close to Login), the @{B}Close@{UB} button quits the program (for now anyway), and the @{B}Settings@{UB} button take you to the umm... er.. I forgot.. Hold on while I get some coffee.. uh, oh, yeah, the @{"settings window" link "screenshots/options_tab.iff/main"}. :)
	
@{B}Settings@{UB}
	There's 4 tabs under settings, @{I}Options@{UI}, @{I}sounds@{UI}, @{I}Logo@{UI}, and @{I}Password@{UI}.
	
@{"Options" link "screenshots/options_tab.iff/main"}
	This is the useful stuff. Well, aside from the password tab (which doesn't work yet, btw). The 2 checkmarks and the 1st cycle menu are startup options, even though I forgot to move the label up one. (oops) The last cycle menu (which I'll probably change to a checkmark) is the login options (hence the "Login option" label above it).
	The @{I}lock on uniconify@{UI} and @{I}lock on quit@{UI} checks do just that. In case somebody gets clever, and wants to mess with the settings or quit the password program before you can block 'em, this requires the user/password to be entered before it quits or uniconfies. Also works when quit or shown from the exchange program or an arexx script.
	The cycle gadget has 3 options in it:
		@{B}Lockout on start@{UB}:    Locks the program when it first starts. It will also lock out on every reboot/power up you have it set up that way (wbstartup, startup-sequence, etc..)
		@{B}Hide on start@{UB}:       Doesn't lock the program, rather it just iconifies it. It'll sit in the background waiting for an arexx 'lock' command, or for you to show/remove it. 
		@{B}Lockout if rebooted@{UB}: This hides the program if the login was interrupted by a reboot/power cycle/power failure/alien invasion/etc... This is for people who want to keep people off their computer, but don't want to be bothered every time they log in (eg. People like me).
		
@{"Sounds" link "screenshots/sounds_tab.iff/main"}
	This is where you can configure which sounds play on which events. Or turn 'em off if you find them annoying (they default to off, anyway). The file button opens an ASL requester, the play button tests the sound, and the label tells you which sound it is.

@{"Logo" link "screenshots/logo_tab.iff/main"}
	The @{I}Logos active@{UI} check lets you turn the logos on or off. I added this one after finding a @{"Gifanim class" system "openurl http://aminet.net/package/dev/mui/MCC_GIFAnim"} on Aminet. Like I mentioned in the @{"intro" link "intro"}, I'm a sucker for eye candy. :D It can eat copious amounts of memory/cpu cycles, so turning it off might be better.

@{"Password" link "screenshots/password_tab.iff/main"}
	This doesn't work yet, but when it does, you can change your password here without wiping all the settings from the program. @{B}Delete envarc:mui/pword.cfg@{UB} (and the same for env:mui/pword.cfg if you really want to kill the settings without rebooting) should do the tring. Program needs to quit first, though.

	You can also set varous options with the MUI settings. The system fonts, Betterstrings, buttons, and groups settings might be worth playing around with.

@{I}Quit@{UI}, @{I}Save@{UI}, @{I}Close@{UI} do what they say they do. :)

@{I}Arexx@{UI}
	The usual MUI commands work, though 'show' and 'quit' will need you to enter a password first. I suppose I should add 'hide' to that, too. oops.. Anyway, the only thing I've added is a 'lock' command, which will trigger the login window. The Arexx port is "PWORD".

	After setting everything is set, the default settings (after enabling the logos. sounds, too, but those don't show well in a screenshot for some reason. :D ) should look like @{"this" link "screenshots/when_launched.iff/main"}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "limitations"
@{jcenter}
@{B}@{U}Limitations@{UB}@{UU}

@{B}@{U}*****  IMPORTANT  *****@{UB}@{UU}
@{jleft}

	This program was designed, in essence, to outsmart my daughter, who is @{B}5 years old@{UB}. If you're looking at this for any kind of real protection, you probably downloaded the wrong program. This one is @{U}easily@{UU} bypassed, disabled, and otherwise rendered useless.
	
	Utilities that can kill tasks (without using commodities interface) will kill this one. Scout can do it. Better yet, scout can bind to an IP address and do it remotely (Not that its a huge threat, getting that to even work is a pain to set up). And it does so in a manner that prevents you from launching it again.
	
	Not sure if launching from a shell makes it vulnerable to ctrl-c signals, but its worth looking into.
	
	The double-mouse-button early startup menu can get you into a shell, where you can edit the startup files, or move it out of wbstartup, or delete it. A simple reboot is all thats needed after that.
	
	Doesn't affect boot floppies.
	
	The password data isn't encrypted, and can be seen with a hex editor. Its saved along with other options in MUIS configuration file (envarc:mui/<proggyname>.cfg).
	
	The "locking" it incorporates is nothing more than a notification that kicks in when the window is deselected, which then reselects the window. Alt-tab commodities, hotkey macros, and screen flipping can get around this @{b}very@{ub} easily.
	
	The default "Boing" noises are extremely entertaining to young children (and annoying to adults), so they'll click around to hear it. Eventually finding a weakness. (My daughter is 5, and I have a $20 bet on her figuring this out)
@{jcenter}
@{b}@{u}Hints@{uu}@{ub}
@{jleft}

	Even with all this, there are some things you can do to make it more effective.
	
	@{B}Its an Amiga@{UB}: Really, how many people know how to use one of these things? If you're concerned with keeping Windows user out, this should be pretty effective. Somebody might have a brilliant idea about using a boot floppy. Try putting a PC boot floppy into an Amiga, reboot, and see what happens. :D Also, while many of the shell commands are @{i}similar@{ui} to DOS/ Whatever implementation of fake dos that win32 stuff uses, they're not going to be the same.
	
	@{B}Stick it on its own screen@{UB}: One of the weaknesses in the re-actiate notify method is the ability for a mouseclick to register on another window before returning focus to the login window. If there's nothing else to click on, this isn't really a big deal. This might be a problem for some RTG users, I've noticed with my Mediator with PCI based SVGA card, flipping screenmodes sometimes crashes the system. But under AGA, it works great! Except for that pesky little flip-to-back gadget on the screen title... Anyway, @{"these settings" link "screenshots/psi_settings.iff/main"} seem to work pretty well.
	
	@{B}Launch before custom drivers@{UB}: Some Amiga hardware requires different drivers to be launched before that hardware will work (some scsi devices, IDE drives larger than 4gb, etc..). If you keep your sensative data on one of these, and passlock the system @{B}before@{UB} the drivers are started, then it really doesn't matter if somebody bypasses it if they don't know how to manually mount the device. (You can rename executable files to something cryptic, or stick mount files somewehere other than devs:dosdrivers to further limit people who do know what they're doing). For example, my 1200 has an 80GB hard drive. When I turn the thing on, the OS can see 4GB of it. It isn't until IDEfix gets installed that the rest becomes available, so if I block IDEfix with a password, anything I have there is inaccessable if I bypass the execute of the startup-script.
	
	@{B}WBstartup@{UB}: If you use a wbstartup manager that lets you bypass the wbstartup programs, don't let it bypass this one if you want it to work under those conditions. Most of such proggies put an Enabled drawer or something in the wbstartup drawer, and will only enable or disable those programs in it. If its in the WBstartup drawer itself, it will be unaffected. Otherwise, you can always launch it from your startup-sequence or user-startup, as long as you run it after MUI does its assigns, and with the needed stack value (8192, might work with less, but if it doesn't, its sometimes a pain to track down).

@ENDNODE

